 <p align="center">
  <font size="+2">
   <b>
This page has links to some of the sites I have found most useful for knife making.<br>
<br>
   </b>
  </font>
If you would like to contact me you can 
<a href="mailto:duncansknives@btopenworld.com">
here.
</a>
<br>
<br>
 <b>
Links:
 </b>
<br>
<br>
Merv Allen is a good teacher who runs enjoyable blacksmithing couses. You can see a page<br>
with contact details
<a href=" http://www.metalwizardry.com/tuition.html" target="_blank">
here.
</a>
<br>
<br>
British Blades is a website devoted to knife making and collecting. The forums are very<br>
interesting, and well moderated. There are also regular hammerins organised, and they are<br>
keen to teach new people about knife making. The site is
<a href="http://www.britishblades.com/forums/index.php" target="_blank">
here.
</a>
<br>
 <br>
Anvilfire is an American blacksmithing site which is a great resource, the link is
<a href="http://www.anvilfire.com/" target="_blank">
here.
</a>
<br>
<br>
I have found the books of Jim Hrisoulas very useful, and definitly recommend them. He has a<br>
site
<a href="http://www.atar.com/old/index.php?module=pagemaster&PAGE_user_op=view_page&PAGE_id=5&MMN_position=6:6" target="_blank">
here.
</a>
and the books can be bought through the BB link to amazon
<a href="http://www.britishblades.com/home/modules.php?modname=custompage&name=bookshop" target="_blank">
here.
</a>
